page.text: This supplemental traffic analysis for the proposed Wildomar Walmart (referred to as “Project”) seeks
to evaluate the potential circulation system deficiencies that may result from the development of the
proposed Project under Sunday peak hour conditions. The Project is located south of Bundy Canyon
Road and west of Monte Vista Drive in the City of Wildomar, and is proposed to consist of a 200,000
square foot Walmart, along with a 7,800 square foot building on an outparcel. The outparcel use is
conceptual, but for the purposes of this supplemental traffic analysis, it was assumed that the building
would consist of 3,900 square feet of specialty retail use and 3,900 square feet of fast-food with drive-
through window restaurant use. The potential circulation system deficiencies that may result from the
development of the Project for weekday AM, weekday PM, and Saturday mid-day peak hour conditions
have been evaluated and documented in the Wildomar Walmart Traffic Impact Analysis (Urban
June 10, 2014, referred to as the “Traffic Study”). The purpose of this
supplemental traffic analysis is to identify potential circulation system deficiencies associated with the
addition of Project traffic in combination with peak traffic demands of the nearby Cornerstone
Community Church, which is located less than one-half mile to the south on Monte Vista Drive.
Based on a comparison of the Opening Year and long-range analysis results contained in this
supplemental analysis to those reported in the Traffic Study, the development of the proposed Project
is not anticipated to result in any additional near-term or long-range deficiencies in addition to those
previously identified in the Traffic Study. The LOS deficiencies for the intersections of the I-15
Northbound Ramps at Baxter Road and Monte Vista Drive at Baxter Road are consistent with the
findings reported in the Traffic Study, however, the improvements necessary to address Sunday
morning peak hour traffic flows exceed those previously identified to address Weekday and Saturday
peak hour traffic flows. This is due to the high demand of inbound and outbound traffic flows focused
at these locations over a 30 minute period leading up to Sunday morning church services held at the
nearby Cornerstone Community Church. Improvements are identified that would comprehensively
address Sunday peak hour conditions. These improvements would also address any potential
Weekday or Saturday peak hour deficiency. Furthermore, future roadway capacity enhancements
consistent with the City’s General Plan designations for both Monte Vista Drive and Baxter Road are
anticipated to address not only weekday, but also Saturday and Sunday peak hour traffic flows.
Consistent with the Traffic Study, the improvements identified in the route concept report for the I-15
Freeway have been analyzed as feasible improvements for General Plan Buildout with Project
conditions. The I-15 Freeway basic freeway segment and merge/diverge ramp junction Sunday peak
hour operations are consistent with or better than resulting operations identified in the Traffic Study
for the weekday AM, PM, and Saturday mid-day peak hours.
In an effort to evaluate intersections near to the Project that could potentially experience operational
deficiencies during Sunday peak hour traffic conditions, the nine intersections indicated on Exhibit 1
were selected as they provide direct access to the proposed Project and the nearby Cornerstone
Consistent with the Traffic Study, the I-15 Freeway mainline segments and ramp junctions immediately
adjacent to the interchanges at Bundy Canyon Road and Baxter Road in both the northbound and
southbound directions have also been assessed.
Consistent with the Traffic Study the following analysis scenarios have been included:
In an effort to determine the actual peak hour of traffic for Sunday conditions, 24-hour roadway
segment counts were conducted at four different locations in the vicinity of the proposed Project and
Cornerstone Community Church on Sunday, February 9, 2014. Based on the 24-hour count data, it was
determined that the peak hours at each of the count locations occurred between 9:00 AM and
12:00PM. Peak hour traffic counts were then conducted at each of the study area intersections on
Sunday, February 23, 2014. The traffic counts are included in Attachment 1 of this letter.
Trip generation rates used to estimate Sunday peak hour Project traffic are shown in Table 1, and a
summary of the Project’s trip generation is provided in Table 2. Consistent with the Traffic Study, the
trip generation rates are based upon data collected by the institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE)
for Free-Standing Discount Superstore (ITE Land Use Code 813), Specialty Retail (ITE Land Use Code
820/826) and Fast-Food with Drive-Through Window restaurant (ITE Land Use Code 934) land uses in
their recently published Trip Generation manual, 9
A more detailed discussion of the Project’s trip generation characteristics can be found in Section 4.1
Project Trip Generation of the Traffic Study.
Trip distribution patterns developed for the Traffic Study have been utilized for this supplemental
traffic analysis effort. A detailed discussion of the Project’s trip distribution characteristics can be
found in Section 4.2 Project Trip Distribution of the Traffic Study.
The assignment of traffic from the Project to the adjoining roadway system is based upon the Project
trip generation, trip distribution, and the arterial highway and local street system improvements that
would be in place by the time of initial occupancy of the Project. Based on the identified Project traffic
generation and trip distribution patterns, Project Sunday peak hour volumes are shown on Exhibit 2.
As shown on Table 3, the study area intersections are currently operating at an acceptable LOS (i.e.,
LOS “C” or “D” or better) during the Sunday peak hour, with the exception of the following three
I-15 Northbound Ramps / Baxter Road – LOS “F”
Sellers Road / Bundy Canyon Road – LOS “E”
Monte Vista Drive / Baxter Road – LOS “E”
Of these, only the intersection of Sellers Road and Bundy Canyon Road was also found to be deficient
for either weekday or Saturday peak hour conditions as reported in the Traffic Study.
As shown on Table 3, the addition of Project traffic is anticipated to result in the following additional
LOS deficiency in addition to those previously identified for Existing (2014) Sunday peak hour traffic
I-15 Southbound Ramps / Baxter Road – LOS “E”
The intersection of I-15 Southbound Ramps and Baxter Road was previously reported as operating at a
deficient LOS (i.e., LOS “F”) during the weekday AM (7AM – 9AM) peak hours.
It should be noted that the development of the Project would include site adjacent improvements such
as the construction of the site adjacent intersections of Sellers Road at Bundy Canyon Road, Monte
Vista Drive at Bundy Canyon Road, and Monte Vista Drive at Canyon Drive. As shown in Table 3, the
intersection of Sellers Road and Bundy Canyon Road is anticipated to operate at acceptable LOS during
E+P Sunday peak hour traffic conditions with the development of Project features.
As shown on Table 3, and consistent with the results previously reported in the Traffic Study for
weekday and Saturday peak hour conditions, Sunday peak hour operations at each of the “off-site”
study area intersections for both Opening Year and General Plan Buildout cumulative traffic conditions
are projected to operate at LOS “E” or “F” without additional capacity enhancements. However, based
on the improvements previously identified in the Traffic Study the study area intersections are
anticipated to operate at an acceptable LOS with the addition of planned improvements consistent
with buildout of the area roadway network.
Intersection operations worksheets are included in Attachments 2 through 7 of this letter. Intersection
operations worksheets detailing the effectiveness of the recommended improvements for all scenarios
Table 7 provides a summary of the recommended intersection improvements for each of the analysis
scenarios. These improvements are consistent with those recommended in the Traffic Study.
A queuing analysis was performed for southbound and northbound off-ramps at the I-15 Freeway at
Bundy Canyon Road and Baxter Road interchanges to assess vehicles queues that may potentially
result in deficient peak hour operations at the ramp-to-arterial intersections and potentially “spill
back” onto the I-15 Freeway mainline under all analysis scenarios assessed for intersection operations
As shown on Table 4, Sunday peak hour off-ramp queues at the southbound and northbound off-ramps
at the I-15 Freeway at Bundy Canyon Road and Baxter Road interchanges are not anticipated to affect
the I-15 Freeway mainline segments under all analysis scenarios.
Freeway ramp queuing analysis worksheets are provided in Attachments 14 through 19 of this letter.
Sunday peak hour mainline directional volumes for each analysis scenario are provided on Exhibits 15
through 20. As shown on Table 5, I-15 Freeway segments analyzed for this study were found to
operate at an acceptable LOS (i.e., LOS “D” or better) during the Existing Sunday peak hour and are
anticipated to continue to operate at acceptable LOS through Opening Year with Project conditions.
As shown on Table 5, the following I-15 Freeway segments analyzed for this study are anticipated to
operate at a deficient LOS (i.e., LOS “E” or worse) for both General Plan Buildout without and with
Project Sunday peak hour traffic conditions:
I-15 Freeway – Southbound, north of Bundy Canyon Road
I-15 Freeway – Southbound, between Bundy Canyon Road and Baxter Road
I-15 Freeway – Southbound, south of Baxter Road
These deficient I-15 Freeway segments are consistent with or less than the deficient segments
identified in the Traffic Study for General Plan Buildout without and with Project traffic conditions.
Basic freeway segment analysis worksheets for each analysis scenario are included in Attachments 20
Long-range future plans for the I-15 Freeway include the addition of one (1) High-Occupancy Vehicle
(HOV) lane in each direction of travel between the I-15/I-215 Freeway interchange and Central Avenue
(SR-74) and one (1) mixed-flow lane in each direction south of the Bundy Canyon interchange per the
route concept report for the I-15 Freeway. Consistent with the Traffic Study, the improvements
identified in the route concept report for the I-15 Freeway have been analyzed as feasible
improvements for General Plan Buildout traffic conditions. As shown on Table 8, all of the improved
freeway mainline segments are anticipated to operate at an acceptable LOS with the proposed
improvements (i.e., LOS “D” or better) during the Sunday peak hour.
Ramp merge and diverge operations were also evaluated for Existing conditions and the results of this
analysis are presented in Table 6. As shown in Table 6, the I-15 Freeway ramp merge and diverge areas
at Bundy Canyon Road and Baxter Road were found to operate at an acceptable LOS (i.e., LOS “D” or
better) during the Existing Sunday peak hour and are anticipated to continue to operate at acceptable
LOS through Opening Year with Project conditions.
Similar to the findings of the basic freeway segment analysis presented previously and as shown on
Table 6, the following I-15 Freeway ramp merge and diverge areas at Bundy Canyon Road and Baxter
Road are anticipated to operate at a deficient LOS (i.e., LOS “E” or worse) for both General Plan
Buildout without and with Project Sunday peak hour traffic conditions:
I-15 Freeway – Southbound, Off-Ramp at Bundy Canyon Road (Diverge)
I-15 Freeway – Southbound, On-Ramp at Bundy Canyon Road (Merge)
I-15 Freeway – Southbound, Off-Ramp at Baxter Road (Diverge)
I-15 Freeway – Southbound, On-Ramp at Baxter Road (Merge)
These deficient ramp junctions are consistent with or less than the deficient ramp junctions identified
in the Traffic Study for General Plan Buildout without and with Project conditions. Sunday peak hour
freeway ramp junction operations analysis worksheets for each analysis scenario are provided in
These deficient ramp junctions are consistent with or less than the deficient ramp junctions presented
in the Traffic Study for General Plan Buildout with Project traffic conditions, with improvements.
Worksheets for General Plan Buildout without and with Project conditions freeway mainline level of
service analysis, with improvements, are provided in Attachments 32 and 33. General Plan Buildout
without and with Project freeway ramp junction level of service analysis worksheets, with
improvements, are provided in Attachments 34 and 35.
Consistent with the Traffic Study, the improvements identified in the route concept report for the I-15
Freeway have been analyzed as feasible improvements for General Plan Buildout traffic conditions.
Table 9 shows that the improved freeway ramp junctions are anticipated to operate at an acceptable
LOS with the construction of an additional mixed-flow lane and HOV lane in both directions of travel
(i.e., LOS “D” or better) during the Sunday peak hour, with the exception of the I-15 Southbound On-
Ramp at Bundy Canyon Road. This anticipated deficiency under General Plan Buildout traffic
conditions is consistent with the Traffic Study.
